==================================================
CHANGE — GORM + goose storage migration
Date: 2026-03-30
==================================================

==================================================
GOAL
==================================================

Replace the pgx/raw-SQL-first storage stack with:

1. GORM for the application persistence layer
2. goose for migration management and startup migration execution

The intent is to move faster on schema and query changes while keeping the
current HTTP/API surface stable during the refactor.

==================================================
WHAT CHANGED
==================================================

1. STORAGE LAYER

  Before:
    internal/storage/db.go            → pgxpool connection wrapper
    internal/storage/*.go             → pgx queries and manual scans

  After:
    internal/storage/db.go            → GORM + sql.DB wrapper
    internal/storage/models.go        → GORM table models + domain mapping
    internal/storage/*.go             → GORM-backed store methods

2. MIGRATIONS

  Before:
    SQL files existed but were run manually via psql

  After:
    goose manages migrations from internal/storage/migrations
    storage.Connect() runs goose Up on startup
    migrations are embedded in the binary

3. DEPENDENCIES

  Added:
    gorm.io/gorm
    gorm.io/driver/postgres
    github.com/pressly/goose/v3
    github.com/lib/pq

==================================================
CURRENT STATE
==================================================

- API server and judge worker still use the same handler/store method shapes
- Startup DB boot now applies goose migrations automatically
- Problem, submission, timer, review, registry, testcase, and mission storage
  paths are being moved behind GORM-backed stores
- Existing SQL seed scripts remain for problem/testcase development data
- The project still uses PostgreSQL and Redis; only the persistence access layer
  and migration runner changed

